.app(Built-In Functions and Operators,appbuiltin,yes)

This table is intended only as a handy guide.  See {"Appendix!" apptype}
for details on polymorphic type conversions.

Some of the functions described here are implemented in only
a particular version of PPL.  Such functions are indicated in
this table by a subscript which indicates the appropriate version
(for example, ~BACKTRACE~{sub(10)} indicates that the function
is definded in PPL-10 only).

.begin nofill tabs 10,15,21,35
.x precedence,table

!<Operator\Prec.\Assoc.\Name\Description>

.fill indent 0,34 preface 0

!<a>#+#!<b>\70\Left\{fn(ADD,a,b)}\Add !<b> to !<a>.

!<a>#-#!<b>\70\Left\{fn(SUB,a,b)}\Subtract !<b> from !<a>.

!<a>#*#!<b>\80\Left\{fn(MUL,a,b)}\Multiply !<a> by !<b>.

!<a>#/#!<b>\80\Left\{fn(DIV,a,b)}\Divide !<a> by !<b>.

!<a>#^#!<b>\90\Right\{fn(POWER,a,b)}\Raise !<a> to the !<b> power
(!<b> must be an ~INT~eger in PPL-11).

.once preface 1
##+#!<a>\100\\{fn(PLUS,a)}\Unary plus (fairly useless, but
included for symmetry).

##-#!<a>\100\\{fn(MINUS,a)}\Return the negative of !<a> (~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~)
or the logical complement of !<a> (~BOOL~).

.once preface 1
!<a>#<#!<b>\50\Left\{fn(LESS,a,b)}\Return ~TRUE~ if !<a> is less than !<b>,
otherwise ~FALSE~.

!<a>#<=#!<b>\50\Left\{fn(LESSEQ,a,b)}\!<a> less than or equal to !<b>.

!<a>#>#!<b>\50\Left\{fn(GR,a,b)}\!<a> greater than !<b>.

!<a>#>=#!<b>\50\Left\{fn(GREQ,a,b)}\!<a> greater than or equal to !<b>.

!<a>#=#!<b>\50\Left\{fn(EQ,a,b)}\!<a> equal to !<b>.

!<a>###!<b>\50\Left\{fn(NOTEQ,a,b)}\!<a> not equal to !<b>.

!<a>#==#!<b>\60\Left\{fn(INSTANCE,a,b)}\~TRUE~ if the value !<a> is an instance of
the predicate !<b>, otherwise ~FALSE~.

.once preface 1
!<a>#&#!<b>\40\Left\{fn(AND,a,b)}\~TRUE~ if !<a> and !<b> are both ~TRUE~, otherwise ~FALSE~.

!<a>#!#!<b>\30\Left\{fn(OR,a,b)}\~TRUE~ if either !<a> or !<b> (or both) is ~TRUE~,
otherwise ~FALSE~.

.once preface 1
!<a>#_#!<b>\20\Right\{fn(ASSIGN,a,b)}\Assign to !<a> a copy of the value of !<b>.

!<a>#__#!<b>\20\Right\{fn(NONCOPY,a,b)}\Make !<a> share the value of !<b>.

.once preface 1
##-->#!<b>\10\\{fn(UGOTO,b)}\Unconditionally go to statement !<b>.
This operation also invoked by the word ~GOTO~.

!<a>#-->#!<b>\10\Left\{fn(CGOTO,a,b)}\If !<a> is ~TRUE~, go to statement !<b>.

.next page
.indent 0,23 tabs 24 preface 1
.macro cat(str) 
.if lines<6 then next page
.skip 2
4str*
.break;
.sectionname _ "str"
. 


.cat(Program Control Functions)

~<<RESET>~\Resets control to global (top-level)
environment, thereby eliminating all nests of function
calls and suspended environments.  Usually required
for text editing.

~<<RESUME>~\Resumes execution from state of suspension.

3<<STOP>(2f3,2n713,2n723,#...#)1\Sets stop codes in function !<f> at statements
2n711, 2n721, etc.  If no statement numbers are supplied,
all statements of !<f> are affected.

3<<UNSTOP>(2f3,2n713,2n723,#...#)1\Removes stop codes; arguments processed as in ~STOP~.

3<<TRACE>(2f3,2n713,2n723,#...#)1\Sets trace codes; arguments processed as in ~STOP~.

3<<UNTRACE>(2f3,2n713,2n723,#...#)1\Removes trace codes; arguments processed as in ~STOP~.

~<<BACKTRACE>~#{sub(10)}\Prints the name and current step number of all
functions currently entered, starting with the most recent function.

{fn(ERASE,a,b,#...#)}\Causes the meanings of identifiers
!<a>, !<b>, etc. to be erased from the current environment.
If ~ERASE~ is called with no arguments,
the entire environment is erased.

.cat(Type Conversion Functions)
{fn(INT,a)}\Converts the value of !<a> to an ~INT~eger,
where !<a> may be any atomic value (~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~, ~BOOL~, ~CHAR~,
or ~NULL~).  A ~BOOL~ is converted to
1 if ~TRUE~ and 0 if ~FALSE~.  A ~CHAR~ is converted
to its equivalent 7ASCII* character code
(see {"Appendix!" appascii}).  ~NULL~ is always converted to zero.

{fn(REAL,a)}\Converts the value of !<a> to a ~REAL~.
Conventions for arguments are the same as for {fn(INT,a)}.

{fn(DBL,a)}\Converts the value of !<a> to a ~DBL~.
Conventions for arguments are the same as for {fn(INT,a)}.

{fn(BOOL,a)}\Converts the value of !<a> to a ~BOOL~.
An ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~ is converted to ~TRUE~
if nonzero and ~FALSE~ if zero.  A ~CHAR~ is converted
to ~TRUE~ if it is ~'T~ or ~'t~, otherwise to ~FALSE~.
~NULL~ is always converted to ~FALSE~.

{fn(CHAR,a)}\Converts the value of !<a> to a ~CHAR~.
If !<a> is numeric (~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~), it is
truncated and used as a character code (see {"Appendix!" appascii}).
A ~BOOL~ is converted to the character ~'T~ if it is
~TRUE~ and ~'F~ if ~FALSE~.  ~NULL~ is converted
to the null character (7ASCII* code 0).

.cat(Input/Output Functions)

{fn(PRINT,a,b,#...#)}\Prints every argument in turn, with
no spaces or line advances between them.

{fn(FORMAT,a,b,#...#)}\Performs formatted numeric output,
using ~STRING~ arguments as format specifications
and numeric arguments as values to be printed in the
given format.

{fn(PRINTSTR,a,b,#...#)}#{sub(10)}\Identical to ~PRINT~, except that the
sequence of characters that would be printed is returned as a ~STRING~.

{fn(FORMATSTR,a,b,#...#)}#{sub(10)}\Identical to ~FORMAT~, except that the
sequence of characters that would be printed is returned as a ~STRING~.

{fn(MSTRING,a)}#{sub(11)}\The ~STRING~ corresponding to the printed
representation of !<a> is returned.  The argument may be an ~INT~,
~REAL~ or ~DBL~.

{fn(WRITE,s)}\Writes all function definitions,
operator definitions, and data definitions onto the
file described by the ~STRING~ !<s>.  If !<s> is omitted,
the output appears on the user's terminal.

{fn(READ,s)}\Reads statements from the file described
by the ~STRING~ !<s>, as if they were coming from
the terminal.  Files written with ~WRITE~ may
be read with ~READ~.

{fn(SAVE,s)}\Saves the current environment in the file
described by the ~STRING~ !<s>.

{fn(RESTORE,s)}\Restores the environment contained in the file
described by the ~STRING~ !<s>.

{fn(INPUT,c,s,m)}\Opens the file described by the ~STRING~
!<s> on channel !<c> in mode !<m> for input (!<m>=~CHAR~ if omitted).

{fn(OUTPUT,c,s,m)}\Opens the file described by the
~STRING~ !<s> on channel !<c> in mode !<m> for output.

{fn(INBYTE,c)}\Reads and returns a byte through channel !<c>.

3<<OUTBYTE>(2c3,2b713,2b723,...,2b7n3)1\Writes bytes 2b711, 2b721, ...#2b7n1
out through channel !<c>.

{fn(INSTMT,c)}\Reads and executes a statement through channel !<c>
and returns its value.

{fn(INSTRING,c)}\Reads and returns a ~STRING~ through channel !<c>.

3<<PRINTF>(2c3,2d713,2d723,...,2d7n3)1\Writes arguments 2d711, 2d721, ...#2d7n1
through channel !<c> in the manner of ~PRINT~.

3<<FORMATF>(2c3,2s713,2s723,...,2s7n3)1\Performs formatted
numeric output on channel !<c> in the manner of ~FORMAT~.

{fn(EOF,c)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if the input file
on channel !<c> is at end-of-file.

3<<CLOSE>(2c713,2c723,...,2c7n3)1\Closes files on channels 2c711, 2c721, ...#2c7n1.
Closes all open files if called with no arguments.

{fn(OPENED,c)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if a file is open on channel !<c>.

~<<FREE.CHANNEL>~\Returns the number of the first free channel,
or ~NULL~ if none are available.

{fn(POSITION,c,p)}\Positions the disk file on channel !<c>
so that the !<p>th byte is referenced next.
Byte numbering begins at 1 on the PDP-10 and at 0 on the
PDP-11.

.cat(Operator Definition Functions)

{fn(UNARY,s,f,p)}\Associates the unary operator described by
the ~STRING~ !<s> with the function !<f>, in such a way that the
use of the operator in a unary context will cause !<f> to be called.
An operator is a sequence of from one to four characters
taken from the set 3!#$%&+-*/^_.:;,<=>\[]()@1#.
The ~INT~eger !<p>, if given, specifies the precedence
of the operator (the value of ~DEF.UNARY.PREC~ is used otherwise).

{fn(BINARY,s,f,p,a)}\Associates the binary operator described
by the ~STRING~ !<s> with the two-argument function !<f>,
in a manner similar to {fn(UNARY,s,f)}.
If given, !<p> and !<a> denote the precedence and associativity
of the operator (the values of ~DEF.BINARY.PREC~ and
~DEF.ASSOC~ are used otherwise).

{fn(UNARY.DEF,o)}#{sub(10)}\Returns as a ~STRING~ the name of the function
associated with the unary operator !<o>, or "" if !<o> is not
defined as a unary operator.

{fn(UNARY.PREC,o)}#{sub(10)}\Returns as an ~INT~ the unary precedence of the
operator !<o>, or zero if !<o> is not defined as a unary operator.

{fn(BINARY.DEF,o)}#{sub(10)}\Returns as a ~STRING~ the name of the function
associated with the binary operator !<o>, or "" if !<o> is not
defined as a binary operator.

{fn(BINARY.PREC,o)}#{sub(10)}\Returns as an ~INT~ the binary precedence of the
operator !<o>, or zero if !<o> is not defined as a binary operator.

{fn(ASSOCIATIVITY,o)}#{sub(10)}\Returns the ~STRING "LEFT"~
or ~"RIGHT"~ denoting the associativity of the binary operator !<o>,
or "" if !<o> is not defined as a binary operator.

{fn(OPERATORS)}#{sub(10)}\Returns a ~TUPLE~ of ~STRING~s enumerating
all currently defined operators (both unary and binary).

{fn(RENUMBER,n)}#{sub(10)}\Adjusts the precedence of all defined operators
so that subsets of equal-precedence operators are separated
by !<n> (which must be a positive ~INT~eger).

{fn(IVERSONIAN)}#{sub(10)}\Changes the precedence of all defined operators,
and changes the values of ~DEF.UNARY.PREC~, ~DEF.BINARY.PREC~, and
~DEF.ASSOC~ so that PPL conforms to Iversonian precedence
(see {"Section!" iversonian}).

.cat(Built-In Functions for User-Defined Data)

{fn(LENGTH,a)}\Returns an ~INT~ which is the number
of components in the value !<a>.  If !<a> is atomic,
{fn(LENGTH,a)} is 1.

{fn(L.BOUND,a)}\Returns the lower bound
of !<a>, where !<a> may be any sequence or structure.

{fn(TYPE,a)}\Returns the data type of the value
!<a> expressed as a ~STRING~.

{fn(CLASS,a)}#{sub(10)}\Returns as a ~STRING~ the class of object denoted
by the global identifier !<a>.  The result is one of the
following:
.begin nofill indent 30 tabs 45 select 3
<<UNASSIGNED>\<<ATOMIC.TYPE>
<<VARIABLE>\<<COMPOSITE.TYPE>
<<SYSTEM.FN>\<<ALTERNATE.TYPE>
<<USER.FN>\<<SELECTOR.NAME>
.end; once preface 0 continue
These class names are also defined as
built-in functions of one argument that return ~TRUE~ if the
argument belongs to the stated class and ~FALSE~ otherwise;
e.g. ~UNASSIGNED(X)~ returns ~TRUE~ if ~X~ is undefined and ~FALSE~ otherwise.  (Only ~UNASSIGNED~ is implemented in PPL-11.)

~<<DATA.DEFINITIONS>~\Returns a ~TUPLE~ of ~STRING~s enumerating
the names of all data definitions made by the user.

{fn(MAKE,t,n,e)}\Constructs a variadic sequence of type !<t> with
!<n> elements, each of whose value is !<e>.

{fn(CONCAT,a,b)}\Concatenates !<a> and !<b>, which must
be variadic sequences of the same type.

{fn(IDENTICAL,a,b)}#{sub(10)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<a> and !<b> refer to (i.e., !<share>) the same object.

.cat(Mathematical Functions)

{fn(ABS,a)}#{sub(11)}\Returns the absolute value of !<a>, which may be
an ~INT~, ~REAL~ or ~DBL~.

{fn(SIN,a)}\Returns the sine of !<a>, where
!<a> is an ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~ expressing
an angle in radians. The result is always ~REAL~ in PPL-10.
In PPL-11, the result is ~REAL~ if !<a> is of type ~INT~ or ~REAL~
and ~DBL~ if !<a> is of type ~DBL~.

{fn(COS,a)}\Returns the cosine of !<a>,
where !<a> is an angle expressed in radians.

{fn(TAN,a)}#{sub(11)}\Returns the tangent of !<a>, where !<a> is an angle expressed
in radians.

{fn(ATAN,a)}\Returns the arctangent of !<a>,
where !<a> is an ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~.
The result is a ~REAL~ or ~DBL~ expressing an angle
in radians.

{fn(SQRT,a)}\Returns the square root of !<a>,
which may be ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~.

{fn(EXP,a)}\Returns the base e exponential of !<a>,
which may be ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~.

{fn(LN,a)}\Returns the natural logarithm of !<a>,
which may be ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~.

{fn(LOG,a)}#{sub(11)}\Returns the common (base 10) logarithm of !<a>.

{fn(RANDOM,a)}\Returns a pseudo-random ~REAL~
in the range zero to one (non-inclusive).
If !<a> (~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~) is
greater than zero, the random number generator is
initialized to !<a>; if less than zero, it is initialized
to the time of day; if equal to zero, no initialization
is performed.

.cat(Miscellaneous Functions)

~<<SYS>~\Causes PPL to return control to the timesharing monitor.
(In PPL-10, control may then be returned to PPL by issuing
the ~REENTER~ command.)

~<<LOGOUT>~#{sub(10)}\Causes PPL to terminate your session and log your job
off the computer.

{fn(SLEEP,n)}\Causes program execution to stop
and proceed after !<n> seconds, where !<n> is an ~INT~eger
less than 64.

~<<DAYTIME>~\Returns as an ~INT~ the time of day in
milliseconds since midnight.
On the PDP-11, this value is in seconds since midnight.

~<<DATE>~\Returns the current date and time as a ~STRING~
in the form "!<dd>-!<mmm>-!<yy>#!<hh>:!<mm>:!<ss>", with a Tab between the
date and time.  For example:  ~"13-SEP-74 13:57:23"~.

~<<FUNCTIONS>~#{sub(10)}\Returns a ~TUPLE~ of ~STRING~s enumerating the names of
all user-defined functions.

~<<VARIABLES>~#{sub(10)}\Returns a ~TUPLE~ of ~STRING~s enumerating the names
of all global variables currently defined.

{fn(NOT,a)}\If !<a> is a ~BOOL~, then the logical
complement of !<a> is returned.  If !<a> is an ~INT~, then
an ~INT~ is returned which is the binary ones' complement
of the internal representation of !<a>.

{fn(IDIV,a,b)}\Identical to {fn(DIV,a,b)}, except that if both !<a> and
!<b> are of type ~INT~, the result is always of type ~INT~ with the
remainder from the division thrown away.

{fn(EXECUTE,s)}#{sub(10)}\Causes PPL to evaluate the ~STRING~ !<s> as program text.

3<<PURGE>(2f713,2f723,...,2f7n3)1#{sub(11)}\Deletes the program text of the functions
2f711, 2f721, ... 2f7n1.  The functions may still be executed, but
may no longer be displayed, edited, or written onto files.
If ~PURGE~ is called with no arguments, all currently defined
functions are affected.
~PURGE~ is used to gain more room when PPL's working space is
exhausted.

{fn(STACKS,n)}#{sub(11)}\Specifies the amount of internal stack storage used
by the PPL evaluator, where !<n> is an ~INT~ greater than zero.
This may be used to continue from errors such as "Control
stack overflow".  3 units of stack space are initially allocated.

~<<PROTOCOL>~#{sub(11)}\All user input and computer output after execution
of the ~PROTOCOL~ command is copied into the file ~PPL.PROTOCOL~ as a
record of the terminal session.

~<<UNPROTOCOL>~#{sub(11)}\Terminates the operation of the ~PROTOCOL~ command
and closes the ~PPL.PROTOCOL~ file.

{fn(EXEC,p,a,b,#...#)}#{sub(11)}\Directs the Unix operating system to
run the program !<p> with arguments !<a>, !<b>, and so forth.
Each of the arguments to ~EXEC~ must be a ~STRING~.
After the conclusion of the program, control returns to PPL.
The ~EXEC~ function does not return a value unless an error
condition occurs in the program being run, in which case the
Unix error number is returned as the value of ~EXEC~.
.end

.app(Automatic Type Conversion,apptype,yes)

In all PPL's built-in functions called by
the execution of operators, a certain amount of
automatic !<type conversion> takes place for operands
that are not suitable.  The circumstances under
which this will take place are explained below;
all other combinations will result in the execution
error message "Illegal argument type".

Arithmetic operators ('+', '-', '*', and '/') convert their
operands as follows: A ~CHAR~ is converted to
an ~INT~ by taking its 7ASCII* character code
(see {"Appendix!" appascii}).  A ~BOOL~ is converted to
the integer value 1 if it is ~TRUE~ and 0 if ~FALSE~.
If the two operands are now not of the same type,
the !<weaker> operand is converted to the type
of the !<stronger>, with strength defined
on the scale ~INT < REAL < DBL~.
(Additionally, if the division of an ~INT~ by another ~INT~
yields a nonzero remainder, both operands are converted
to ~REAL~s and the result is ~REAL~.)

The unary operator '-' allows
an operand of type ~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~, or ~BOOL~.
The result is always of the same type as
the operand.  For ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~, the
result is the arithmetic negation of the
operand, whereas for ~BOOL~ it is the
logical complement.

Four of the relational operators ('<', '<=', '>', and '>=')
allow only operands of type ~INT~, ~REAL~, and ~DBL~.
If the two operand types are not the same, conversion
is performed as for arithmetic operations.
PPL-11 also allows these operators to be used with ~STRING~s
as described in {"Section!" builtintypes}.

Two of the relational operators ('=' and '#')
allow operands of type ~BOOL~ or ~CHAR~ if
both operands are of the same type.  No conversion
is necessary in these cases.  Conversion for
arithmetic types is the same as for the other four
relational operators.
The '=' and '#' operators may also be used to
compare ~STRING~s; two ~STRING~s are equal if and only
if they are the same length and corresponding characters
are the same.  A future version of PPL
will allow the comparison of arbitrary user-defined
data.

In PPL-10, Boolean operations ('&' and '!') carry a somewhat
more involved convention.  If both operands are
of type ~BOOL~, then no conversion is necessary.
Otherwise, at least one operand must be of
type ~INT~ or an error will result.
A logical operation between non-~BOOL~s
consists of the appropriate operation performed
bitwise between the operands, using the
36-bit PDP-10 hardware representations for
~INT~, ~REAL~, and ~DBL~.  If a ~BOOL~
is one of the operands, it is represented
as a word containing all zeroes (for ~FALSE~) or
all ones (for ~TRUE~).  The result
of the operation has the type of the 'stronger'
of its operands, with strength defined on the
scale ~BOOL < CHAR < INT < REAL < DBL~.
For completeness, we present the format of the
internal representation for the five atomic types:

.begin indent 0,8 tabs 9
~INT~\A 36-bit 2's complement integer (see PDP-10 System
Reference manual).

~REAL~\A 36-bit hardware floating point number.

~DBL~\A 72-bit hardware floating point number (in KA10 format).

~CHAR~\A right-justified integer 7-bit 7ASCII* character
code.

~BOOL~\A word containing the integer 0 (for ~FALSE~)
or 1 (for ~TRUE~).
.end

In PPL-11, only ~BOOL~s and ~INT~s are allowed as operands of '&' and '!'.

The ~GOTO~ operation (also the '-->' operator
and the ~UGOTO~ and ~CGOTO~ built-in functions)
requires a right operand which is
an ~INT~.  Note that a relocatable
line number, which is what is usually used, is really an ~INT~
with special properties which come into play
only during text editing.  The left operand
of the '-->' operator must be a ~BOOL~.

The '==' operator allows any value as its left
operand.  Its right operand must be a valid predicate;
that is, an atomic type name (~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~,
~BOOL~, or ~CHAR~), a user-defined data type name (e.g. ~COMPLEX~),
or a name defined in an alternate definition (e.g. ~ARITH~).

.app(Summary of Editing Commands,appediting,yes)
.begin nofill tabs 9

To display the text of a function ~F~:
3\?F1

To display line 5 of the function ~F~:
3\?F[5]1

To display lines 5 through 7 of the function ~F~:
3\?F[5:7]1

To open function ~F~ for editing, starting at line 3:
3\$F[3]1

While within a function, move to line 2 for editing:
3\[2]1

To insert a statement between 4 and 5:
3\[4.5]1

To close the function (causing renumbering and translation):
3\$1

Control characters:

.fill indent 2,14 tabs 15 preface 0

Return\Terminate current statement, sequence to next.

Rubout\Delete last character (Control-A under Tenex).

Control-U\Delete current typein and try again
(Control-Q under Tenex).

Escape\Open current text for
advanced text editing.
.end

Text editor commands ('$' stands for Escape):

.begin skip 1 indent 2,35 preface 0 tabs 36
3[!<r>] !<n> REPLACE !<string>{sub(1)} $ !<string>{sub(2)}1\In the range !<r>, replace
!<n> occurrences of !<string>{sub(1)} by !<string>{sub(2)}.

3[!<r>] !<n> DELETE !<string>1\In the range !<r>, delete !<n> occurrences of !<string>.

3[!<r>] !<n> INSERT !<string>{sub(1)} $ !<string>{sub(2)}1\In the range !<r>, insert !<string>{sub(1)}
after the first !<n> occurrences of !<string>{sub(2)}, or at the current pointer
position if !<string>{sub(2)} is not specified.

3[!<r>] !<n> FIND !<string>1\In the range !<r>, leave the pointer after the !<n>th
occurrence of !<string>.

3[!<r>] TYPE1\Type out all statements in the range !<r>.

3[!<r>] KILL1\Delete all statements in the range !<r>.

3VERBOSE1\Perform an automatic TYPE command after every operation
that uses string arguments.

3CONCISE1\Leave verbose mode.
.end

.app(Summary of Data Definitions,appdata,yes)

.begin nofill tabs 9,25
.skip 1
Structure definition:
3\$COMPLEX = [RP:REAL, IP:REAL]1
.skip 1
Where\~COMPLEX~ is the new type name,
\~RP~, ~IP~ are selector names for the components, and
\~REAL~ is the element type for both components.
.skip 1
Sequence definition (variadic, i.e. indefinite upper bound):
3\$VECTOR = [1: ] ARITH1
.skip 1
Where\~VECTOR~ is the new type name,
\1 is the lower bound for indexing,
\the upper bound is unspecified, and
\~ARITH~ is the element type.
.skip 1
Sequence definition (fixed):
3\$ROW4 = [1:4] INT1
.skip 1
Where\~ROW4~ is the new type name,
\1 is the lower bound,
\4 is the upper bound, and
\~INT~ is the element type.
.skip 1
Alternate definition:
3\$ARITH = INT ! REAL ! DBL1
.skip 1
Where\~ARITH~ is the new predicate, and
\~INT~, ~REAL~, and ~DBL~ are the types that are
\  to be considered instances of an ~ARITH~.
.skip 1
Built-in data definitions:
.skip 1
3\$STRING = [1: ] CHAR
\$TUPLE = [1: ] GENERAL
\$ATOMIC = INT!REAL!DBL!BOOL!CHAR!NONE1
.skip 1
Also:\3SEQUENCE1\Any fixed-length sequence.
\3V.SEQUENCE1\Any variadic sequence.
\3GENERAL1\Any data type.
.end

