.app(The Syntax of PPL,appsyntax,yes)

The following is the BNF (Backus Normal Form) grammar of PPL,
which was used to generate its parse tables.
<atom> stands for any identifier or constant,
and <op> stands for any unary or binary operator.
<rpad> is an end-of-line marker analagous to
Return.  The character '|' is the metasymbol
used to separate alternatives.
The lexical analyzer determines the decomposition
of operator strings into operators and special symbols,
and also processes labels; thus, that mechanism does
not appear here.  The redundancy of <form> and <form-1>
is necessary to make the grammar unambiguous
(by avoiding the 'dangling ~ELSE~' problem) and has
no other significance.
The ambiguity in the rules defining <expression> is resolved
through application of the precedence of the operators involved.

.begin nofill tabs 17
.skip 1
<statement> ::=\<form> <rpad> | <rpad> |
\<for-prefix> <dothru> <expression> <rpad>

<form> ::=\<s-form> ; <form> | <s-form> | <if-prefix> <form> |
\<if-prefix> <form-1> <els> <form> |
\<for-prefix> <do> <form> |
\~WHILE~ <expression> <do> <form>

<form-1> ::=\<s-form> ; <form-1> | <s-form> |
\<if-prefix> <form-1> <els> <form-1> |
\<for-prefix> <do> <form-1> |
\~WHILE~ <expression> <do> <form-1>

<s-form> ::=\<expression> | ~GOTO~ <expression> |
\~RETURN~ | ~RETURN~ <expression> |
\~REPEAT~ <form> ~UNTIL~ <expression>

<expression> ::=\<op> <expression> | <term> |
\<expression> <op> <expression>

<term> ::=\<atom> | <term> ( <list> ) | <term> ( ) |
\<term> [ <list> ] | [ <list> ] | [ ] | ( <form> )

<list> ::=\<form> | <list> , <form>

<if-prefix> ::=\~IF~ <expression> ~THEN~ | <expression> =>

<for-prefix> ::=\~FOR~ <for-list> | <for-list>

<for-list> ::=\<expression> : <expression> |
\<expression> : <expression> : <expression>

<do> ::=\~DO~ | ;

<dothru> ::=\~DOTHRU~ | ;;

<els> ::=\~ELSE~ | ::
.end

.app(Known Problems in PPL,appproblems,yes)
.x System Errors

PPL is still under development and
will remain so indefinitely.  Thus, it is
always possible that an internal error will
occur.  Furthermore, PPL is not fully 'user-proof'
in several areas;  that is, the user can do
something so bad as to cause an internal error.

When a system error occurs, a ~RESET~ is executed
automatically and a message is printed.
If the attempted recovery fails, control returns
to the timesharing monitor
(signified by a printout of a period or at-sign at the left margin).
Nearly all possible errors are detected internally, and
PPL is generally able to recover.
'Recovery' in this sense means that after PPL
does an implicit ~RESET~, functions, data definitions,
operator definitions, and global data are intact.

Upon successful recovery, it
is wise at this point to save the
current environment
(using the ~SAVE~ procedure), and also
to save programs and definitions separately
using ~WRITE~.
This is because internal data might
have been affected by the error in such
a way that a non-recoverable error could
occur later.
Note that internal errors are not eliminated
by ~SAVE~ing and ~RESTORE~ing the environment.

There are a number of ways
in which a user may bring about a system
error.  A few will be mentioned here
to enable the user to know what to avoid.

For example, using the '__' operator (~NONCOPY~ assignment),
it is possible to create structures that
are 'cyclic' in nature.  For example:

.examp
\X_[2,0,3]
\X[2]__X
.end

There is nothing illegal about this.  However,
PPL is not, at present, able to
print out such a structure intelligently;  if an attempt is
made to do so, a system pushdown-list overflow
will occur (PPL always recovers successfully
in this case).  For example:

.examp
\X
[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,[2,
[2,[2,[SYSTEM ERROR DETECTED AT 400502; PDL OV
[RESET EXECUTED]
.end

PPL makes heavy demands
on core memory resources.
In the event PPL runs out of working space
and cannot obtain more from the time-sharing
monitor, it is forced to stop execution.  The message
"Pointer zone exhausted" or "Data zone exhausted"
is printed in this case. It is not usually possible
to continue unless more memory can be obtained.
If this error occurs unexpectedly in PPL-10, it is wise to check
for an unintentional
infinite regress caused by redefining a common
built-in operator and using it within the function
associated with the new meaning of the operator (see {"Section!" opdef}).
(In PPL-11, this error will result in a "Control stack overflow".)

The designers of PPL would appreciate
reports of system errors and other problems;  only in this way can
attempts be made to remove them.
However, such reports, to be useful, must
be as complete as possible.  Sample typescripts and
program listings should be included, and reports should
be submitted to one of the individuals listed in the
Introduction ({"Section!" ack}).

.app(Supplementary Information for PPL-10,apsup10)
.asec(|Erasing Data Definitions|)

Erasing a data definition (using the
~ERASE~ procedure) is generally not a good idea.
If it must be done, the user should take great
care that he has first erased !<all> instances
of data constructed according to that definition.
(In PPL-10, failure to observe this precaution may lead to
system errors such as "Garbage collection error, data definition missing".)

.asec(|Special Handling of the REENTER Command|)

PPL-10's normal handling of the monitor ~REENTER~
command is to set a flag, then resume whatever it was doing
before.  At a later, more convenient point in PPL's
execution cycle, this flag is tested, and
suspension occurs if it is set.  However, it is possible
that this operation will fail, either because input has
been requested from a hung device or because of an internal
error within PPL itself.  If this occurs, performing
a second double-Control-C, ~REENTER~ operation
will cause PPL to attempt an automatic
~RESET~ and return control to the user in the top-level
environment.

.asec(|Other Known Bugs and Deficiencies|)

This section describes problems that were known at the
time this manual was prepared.  These problems
may be fixed in a future version of PPL.

If a parameterless function is called with arguments,
the error is not detected at the time of the call.
Instead, the call is made, and an error
usually occurs when the function returns.

If the user performs a Control-C, ~REENTER~ operation
when PPL is requesting input from the terminal via ~INSTMT(0)~ or
~INSTRING(0)~, a system error sometimes occurs.
Thus, it is suggested that ? and ?" be used in place
of ~INSTMT(0)~ and ~INSTRING(0)~.

At present, the operation of the built-in function ~READ~
consists simply of opening the specified file, then redirecting
subsequent input requests to that file rather than the user's
console.  ~READ~ does not itself perform any input.
This means that a running program cannot successfully execute
a ~READ~ to read in new functions and/or data.  For now,
the following user-defined function may be used to perform
the desired operation:

.examp
\$XREAD(F); C,T
   [1]\INPUT(C_FREE.CHANNEL,F)
   [2]\WHILE -EOF(C) DO T_INSTMT(C)
   [3]\CLOSE(C)
   [4]\$
.end

If end-of-file is encountered within a function definition
being read from a file, the correct error message will be
printed, but then a system error will occur.  The result
will be as if the function in question had never been opened.

It is not presently possible to write a comment on a function header (the first line of a function definition) or on a data definition.

.asec(Old Text Editor)

Editing in PPL-10 versions prior to 53 is limited to moving through a program
to replace, insert and delete single lines and to edit the actual
text of a statement using the character editor described below.
None of the editor command structure for more advanced editing ({"Section" charedit}) is
supported.
The mechanism for insertion and replacing lines remains the same,
as does the facility for sequencing through the program steps.
Only two editing operations are entirely changed by the new editor:
the deletion of lines and editing within lines.

In order to delete an existing program step under the old editor,
the user must sequence to the appropriate line in the usual manner
as if to replace or edit that line.  Typing a control-G (^G) deletes
the current line without replacing it.  For example, the following
editing sequence deletes line [6] of ~$TEST~.

.examp
	$TEST[6]
   [6]	^G
   [7]	$
.end

Intraline editing is provided from the old PPL editor by entering a
special character editing mode, invoked by pressing the Escape key.  Depending on when Escape is typed,
PPL will now take one of three actions.  If no function is open
and Escape is the first character typed on a line, PPL will open the
most recently typed in statement for character editing.
If it is not the first character on a line, the current line is
terminated and opened for editing.  If a function is open
at the time, and Escape is the first character typed after PPL
types the line number, then the previous text of that statement
is opened for editing if it exists, otherwise the statement
most recently typed in by the user is opened.

The selected text is now retyped by PPL on the next line.  (If the
statement contains continuation lines, only the first line is typed).
PPL then prints ~EDIT>~ and positions the typehead below the first
character on the line.

The user now has several options.  If a printing character, a space,
or a Tab is typed, it replaces the character immediately above the
typehead.  If a Rubout (Control-A on Tenex) is typed, it deletes
the character above the typehead; a back-slash (\) is echoed.
Characters in the existing line may be passed over without change
by the use of any of the following control characters:

.begin indent 0,15 tabs 16
Control-N\Passes by and echoes the Next character on the line.

Control-E\Passes over and echoes every character until the End
of the current line (leaving the typehead at the end).

Control-T\Passes over and echoes Ten characters.

Control-S!<c>\Waits for a single search character !<c> to be
typed in, then passes over and echoes characters until the search
character is found.  Successive continuation lines will be searched
if required until that character is found.  If it is not found, the
typehead will be left at the end of the entire statement.

Control-X\Passes over and echoes characters until a separator
character (something other than a letter or digit) is reached.
.end

Additionally, there are a number of control characters with
special functions during character editing mode.  These are:

.begin indent 0,15 tabs 16
Line-Feed\Moves to and retypes the next continuation line
if one exists.  This line may now be edited.

Escape\Retypes the first line of the statement and re-opens
it for editing.

Control-R\Retypes the current line of the statement and
re-opens it for editing.

Return\Closes the entire statement, with changes, and enters
it just as if the user had typed it directly.  If a function is open,
the statement is stored; if not, the statement is immediately executed.

Control-A\(Control-B on Tenex)  This character is used for
insertion.  PPL responds by spacing down one line and printing
an upward arrow.  This points to the character on the current line
before which characters are to be inserted.  All printing characters, as well as space and Tab, may now be typed for insertion.  In this
mode, the Rubout key (control-A on Tenex) will delete and echo
the most recently inserted character (if all inserted characters
have been rubbed out, it will start deleting characters before
the insertion in the current line).  Insertion mode is terminated
by typing any control character, which will have its normal function.
.end

One useful rule to remember with regard to control characters is
that all characters recognized by PPL cause some visible action.  If
an illegal control character is typed, it is simply ignored.

.app(Supplementary Information for PPL-11,apsup11)

In concept, PPL-10 and PPL-11 are identical.
However, due to architectural differences between the two
machines and the fact that the implementations are at slightly
different stages of development, some incompatabilities do exist.
This section describes a number of these differences and reflects
the state of PPL-11 through Version 7.

.asec(|PPL under the Unix Operating System|)

The Unix operating system has its own set of conventions that
affect the operation of PPL-11, and in some cases result in
incompatabilities with respect to the PDP-10 version.
Several of these areas are described below.

Character conventions in Unix are different from those on the
PDP-10 in two important respects.
First, the standard end-of-line sequence for Unix is the single
linefeed character (7ASCII* 10 decimal) as opposed to PDP-10
convention which uses the two-character Return/Line-Feed
sequence.
Secondly, the standard case for alphabetic characters in Unix
is lower case rather than the PDP-10 upper case standard.
Programs exist on the PDP-11 for converting files between
Unix and PDP-10 format, and are described in the Harvard
Terminal User's Guide.

To simplify the problem caused by lower case operation,
identifiers and ~STRING~s differing only in case are considered
to be equal.
Single characters, however, must currently match in case.

Like most Unix subsystems, PPL may be given arguments when
it is first started from the Shell.
Arguments are of the form:

.examp
\[-E] [-N] [-M] [!<pathname>.ENV]
.end

where brackets indicate that the argument is optional.
The ~-E~ switch, if included, will prevent PPL from using
its error message file and cause PPL to report errors using a numerical
code.
The ~-N~ switch prevents PPL from writing out its standard header
message.
The ~-M~ switch is useful only in special versions of PPL which
include a metering package.
For such implementations, the ~-M~ switch causes PPL to write out
its symbol table.
If the !<pathname>~.ENV~ specification is used, PPL will restore
the specified environment.

PPL will execute commands from the primary input port,
even if the primary input port is not the user's teletype.
If, however, an end of file is encountered when some other
port is used as the primary input, PPL will exit to the monitor.

On the PDP-10, files are not actually stored permanently until
the file is closed.
In Unix, files exist permanently immediately after they are
opened.
It is still necessary to use the ~CLOSE~ command, however.

.asec(|Memory Management|)


PPL-11 can provide the user with approximately 29K of
working space.
This 29K is divided into three logical pieces.

.begin nofill group tabs 9

\(1)  Control Stack
\(2)  Name/Object Stack
\(3)  General Working Space
.end

Provided that the user does not press too closely to the
29K limit, PPL's core allocation policies work silently
in the background and the user need never worry.  However,
if PPL ever runs out of room for any one of these three logical
pieces, an error message will be issued.
The individual cases are discussed below.

!<Control Stack Overflow.>  This occurs when a program is deeply
nested in recursive calls and PPL has no more space to allocate
for the Control Stack.
When this error occurs, PPL will print a suitable error message
and perform an automatic ~RESET~.

The best way to circumvent this problem is to keep the number
of recursive calls down.
The user should note, however, that by keeping the
Name/Object stack and General Working Space size to a minimum,
the user can insure that the maximum amount of space is
available to the Control Stack.

!<Name/Object Stack Overflow.>  This error occurs whenever
PPL's internal Name or Object Stack overflows.  The first time
this error occurs, PPL will suspend execution and the
user may examine the values of local variables.
He may also continue execution.
If the Name/Object Stack again overflows, however, an automatic
~RESET~ will occur.

!<Insufficient General Working Space.>  When PPL can not
obtain enough general working space, it will suspend execution
and print a warning message.
The user may attempt to continue at this point, although such
an attempt will usually fail, unless he deletes enough material
(programs or data) to provide enough working space for PPL to
continue.
To reduce storage requirements for programs, a special
function ~PURGE~ is defined which deletes the program text
from user functions.
Such functions may still be executed, but may not be examined,
edited or written out.
In light of this, ~PURGE~ should only be used after the program
text has been saved using the ~WRITE~ command.
~PURGE~ may be called with no arguments, in which case, all
functions will be purged, or individual functions may be given
as arguments.
Using ~PURGE~ typically lowers the storage required for functions
by about 30%.

The amount of memory allocated to the three regions may be changed
by calling the function {fn(STACKS,n)} which causes !<n> units of core
to be allocated to each of the three regions.

.asec(|Special PPL Versions|)

Certain more-recent releases of PPL may contain a compiler which
allows efficient machine code equivalents of PPL programs to be
produced from user program text.
Using the compiler, in some cases, can result in an improvement
in program execution time of a factor of four.

New releases may also contain the ~INGRES~ relational data base
as a sublanguage embedded in the PPL system.
This allows the user to employ a wide variety of data manipulation
operations with improved efficiency.

Further infomation concerning these versions will be included in
the documentation which accompanies the particular release.

.asec(|Additional Notes|)

There are a number of built-in functions that are implemented
in only one of the two major implementations of PPL.
Generally, these differences, along with any differences
in the operation of particular functions, have been described
in the manual.
Additional incompatabilities are noted here.

When typed into PPL, ~STRING~s are limited in length to 200
characters.

.send contents 
.skip 1
. 
